'''無肉日'''的訴求是希望大眾能夠在一週間的固定某幾天能夠避免或不吃肉。而週一和週四是最普遍的選擇。另外還有一些無肉運動是鼓勵大眾一週、一個月或甚至永遠不吃肉。

== 歷史沿革 ==
戒肉在歷史上主要是基於宗教理由 (例如: 週五[[齋戒|齋戒]]日)。[[漢傳佛教|漢傳佛教]]主張在家信眾於至少於農曆每月初一、十五茹素，稱之為「朔望齋」，亦有於[[六齋日|六齋日]]、[[十齋日|十齋日]]茹素，以及於佛、菩薩的誕日茹素。循道衛理教會在[[大齋期|大齋期]]期間，信眾普遍認為每週一日不吃肉是一種懺悔[[贖罪|贖罪]]的方式。<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?ptid=1&mid=2872|title=What does The United Methodist Church say about fasting?|accessdate=27 April 2014|publisher=The United Methodist Church|archive-date=2010-03-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100310224612/http://archives.umc.org/interior.asp?ptid=1&mid=2872|dead-url=no}}</ref>[[聖公會|<nowiki/>]] [[普世聖公宗|普世聖公宗]]([[美國聖公會|美國聖公會]]) 以及[[羅馬天主教會|羅馬天主教會]]的傳統也奉行週五齋戒日。<ref name="Buchanan2009">{{cite book|title=The A to Z of Anglicanism|last=Buchanan|first=Colin|date=4 August 2009|publisher=Scarecrow Press|isbn=9780810870086|page=182|quote=In the 1662 Book of Common Prayer, there is a list of "Days of Fasting, or Abstinence," consisting of the 40 days of Lent, the ember days, the three rogation days (the Monday to Wednesday following the Sunday after Ascension Day), and all Fridays in the year (except Christmas, if it falls on a Friday).}}</ref><ref name="Green2006">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jH2DrcY2DXMC&pg=PA224|title=Dealing with Death: A Handbook of Practices, Procedures and Law|last=Green|first=Jennifer|date=25 May 2006|publisher=Jessica Kingsley Publishers|accessdate=27 April 2014|isbn=9781846425127|page=224|quote=Friday is a day of abstinence and self-denial for Catholics in health, and, by tradition, this became a meat-free day.|archive-date=2017-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124050219/https://books.google.com/books?id=jH2DrcY2DXMC&pg=PA224|dead-url=no}}</ref> 在歷史上， 聖公會和天主教國家會強制所有人民在大齋期的某些特定日全面禁止葷食。比方說在英國， 屠夫及餐館老闆受制於高額擔保費必須保證每週的週五及週六不得屠殺或販售肉品。<ref name="BarrowsRoom1991">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=o-wmSdtGer0C&pg=PA340|title=Drinking: Behavior and Belief in Modern History|last2=Room|first2=Robin|publisher=University of California Press|accessdate=27 April 2014|year=1991|isbn=9780520070851|page=340|quote=The main legally enforced prohibition in both Catholic and Anglican countries was that against meat. During Lent, the most prominent annual season of fasting in Catholic and Anglican churches, authorities enjoined abstinence from meat and sometimes "white meats" (cheese, milk, and eggs); in sixteenth- and seventeenth-century England butchers and victuallers were bound by heavy recognizances not to slaughter or sell meat on the weekly "fish days," Friday and Saturday.|last1=Barrows|first1=Susanna|archive-date=2017-01-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170124101129/https://books.google.com/books?id=o-wmSdtGer0C&pg=PA340|dead-url=no}}</ref> 在[[東正教|東正教]], 週三和週五是齋戒日。<ref name="Vitz1991">{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hrdUYzuAO14C&pg=PA80|title=A Continual Feast|last=Vitz|first=Evelyn Birge|publisher=Ignatius Press|accessdate=27 April 2014|year=1991|isbn=9780898703849|page=80|quote=In the Orthodox groups, on ordinary Wednesdays and Fridays no meat, olive oil, wine, or fish can be consumed.|archive-date=2020-07-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200729125909/https://books.google.com/books?id=hrdUYzuAO14C&pg=PA80|dead-url=no}}</ref> 在[[信義宗|信義宗]]的歷史上，週五和週六是他們的齋戒日。<ref name="Lund2002">{{cite book|title=Documents from the History of Lutheranism, 1517–1750|last=Lund|first=Eric|date=January 2002|publisher=Fortress Press|isbn=9781451407747|page=166|quote=Of the Eating of Meat: One should abstain from the eating of meat on Fridays and Saturdays, also in fasts, and this should be observed as an external ordinance at the command of his Imperial Majesty.}}</ref>

備戰時期所實施的糧食定量配給或在一些經濟蕭條的國家也有無肉日的規定。 (例如:[[第一次世界大戰|第一次世界大戰]]時，加拿大以及美國實施週二無肉日<ref>[http://www.city.waterloo.on.ca/VeteransGreen/PrinterFriendly.aspx?tabid=1381 "Making Do with Less": Rationing in Canada] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20121216045606/http://www.city.waterloo.on.ca/VeteransGreen/PrinterFriendly.aspx?tabid=1381 |date=2012-12-16 }}</ref> ，同時也實施週三無麥日)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pbs.org/food/the-history-kitchen/history-meatless-mondays/|title=History of Meatless Mondays | The History Kitchen | PBS Food|accessdate=2015-11-02|date=|publisher=Pbs.org|archive-date=2021-02-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20210217181424/https://www.pbs.org/food/the-history-kitchen/history-meatless-mondays/|dead-url=no}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://dinersjournal.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/23/the-way-we-ate-the-year-harry-truman-passed-on-pumpkin-pie/ |title=The Way We Ate: The Year Harry Truman Passed on Pumpkin Pie |access-date=2017-03-14 |archive-date=2019-10-20 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191020094854/https://dinersjournal.blogs.nytimes.com/2009/11/23/the-way-we-ate-the-year-harry-truman-passed-on-pumpkin-pie/ |dead-url=no }}</ref> 。

在[[波蘭人民共和國|波蘭人民共和國]]時期, 因為市場力量的趨動，政府鼓勵人民響應無肉日。他們的目標是減少肉品的消費，而鼓勵麵粉製品的消費。依照傳統，他們的無肉日是週五、週一或週三。

== {{Anchor|Ecology and normal society}}生態與社群 ==
社會開始重新引進「無肉日」運動主要訴求是為了減少工業化養殖業，推動素食和維根[[純素|純素]]生活，以達到減緩人為氣候變遷，同時增進人體健康和動物福利等。

